\section*{Introduction}

The shift toward virtual learning has significantly transformed educational practices, especially following global events such as the pandemic. While both virtual and conventional classrooms aim to educate students, they differ in structure, delivery, and interaction. This paper explores the **differences and similarities** between teaching methodologies in these two environments, their **advantages**, and **disadvantages**, while accounting for unique variables in each setting.

\section*{Differences Between Virtual and Conventional Classrooms}

\subsection*{1. Structure and Environment}

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Conventional Classroom:} 
        \begin{itemize}
            \item In-person, face-to-face interaction.
            \item Structured environment with fixed schedules.
            \item Use of physical materials (books, whiteboards, etc.).
        \end{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Virtual Classroom:}
        \begin{itemize}
            \item Remote, asynchronous or synchronous learning.
            \item Variable schedules depending on student availability.
            \item Reliance on digital tools (e.g., Zoom, Google Meet, LMS platforms).
        \end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{2. Interaction and Engagement}

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Conventional Classroom:}
        \begin{itemize}
            \item Real-time, non-verbal cues (body language, eye contact).
            \item Group work and hands-on activities are easier to facilitate.
        \end{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Virtual Classroom:}
        \begin{itemize}
